  "local_port": 45630,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why isn\u2019t Pok\u00e9mon GO working?",
  "response": "There could be several reasons why Pok\u00e9mon GO isn't working for you. Here are some common issues and solutions:\n\n1. **Server Issues:**\n   - Sometimes, the game's servers may be down for maintenance or experiencing high traffic. Check the official Pok\u00e9mon GO Twitter account or other social media channels for any announcements about server status.\n\n2. **Internet Connection:**\n   - Ensure your device has a stable internet connection. Try switching between Wi-Fi and mobile data to see if that resolves the issue.\n\n3. **App Updates:**\n   - Make sure your Pok\u00e9mon GO app is up to date. Developers often release updates to fix bugs and improve performance.\n\n4. **Device Compatibility:**\n   - Verify that your device meets the game's system requirements. Older devices may struggle to run the latest version of the game.\n\n5. **Location Services:**\n   - Pok\u00e9mon GO requires access to your device's location services. Ensure that location permissions are enabled for the app in your device settings.\n\n6. **Battery Saving Mode:**\n   - If your device is in battery saving mode, it might interfere with the game. Try turning off battery saving mode and see if the game works.\n\n7. **Reinstalling the App:**\n   - Sometimes, reinstalling the app can resolve issues. Make sure to back up your account first by linking it to a Google or Pok\u00e9mon Trainer Club account.\n\n8. **Cache and Data:**\n   - Clearing the app's cache and data can sometimes help. Go to your device settings, find the Pok\u00e9mon GO app, and clear its cache and data (note that this might log you out and you'll need to log back in).\n\nIf none of these solutions work, you might want to reach out to Niantic's support team for further assistance.",
